so keep the questions
coming so we'll

00:00:36.403 --> 00:00:38.739 align:middle line:84%
get to them later
on in the show.

00:00:38.739 --> 00:00:41.475 align:middle line:84%
So, today we're talking
about space and time,

00:00:41.475 --> 00:00:45.078 align:middle line:84%
and what it means to live
in a holographic universe.

00:00:45.078 --> 00:00:46.813 align:middle line:84%
And we're talking
about all of this

00:00:46.813 --> 00:00:49.416 align:middle line:84%
from the perspective
of quantum physics

00:00:49.416 --> 00:00:52.119 align:middle line:84%
so that we can find out how
to take charge of our lives

00:00:52.119 --> 00:00:53.487 align:middle line:90%
at the quantum level.

00:00:53.487 --> 00:00:55.522 align:middle line:84%
And joining me is
Fred Allan Wolfe.

00:00:55.522 --> 00:00:56.423 align:middle line:90%
He's a physicist.

00:00:56.423 --> 00:00:59.326 align:middle line:84%
And he's got 14 books
on quantum physics.

00:00:59.326 --> 00:01:01.862 align:middle line:84%
One of them is called "Time
Loops and Space Twists."

00:01:01.862 --> 00:01:04.765 align:middle line:84%
He's also known
affectionately as Dr. Quantum.

00:01:04.765 --> 00:01:07.901 align:middle line:84%
He has a really wonderful way of
taking these abstract concepts

00:01:07.901 --> 00:01:10.604 align:middle line:84%
and simplifying them so
that we can apply them

00:01:10.604 --> 00:01:11.605 align:middle line:90%
to our own lives.

00:01:11.605 --> 00:01:12.806 align:middle line:90%
Welcome to the show.

00:01:12.806 --> 00:01:14.741 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED ALLAN WOLFE: Thank
you very much, Lisa.

00:01:14.741 --> 00:01:15.876 align:middle line:90%
Pleasure to be here.

00:01:15.876 --> 00:01:18.145 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: As you can see,
Dr. Quantum's a lot of fun.

00:01:18.145 --> 00:01:19.146 align:middle line:90%
So this really helps--

00:01:19.146 --> 00:01:19.379 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: I hope so.

00:01:19.379 --> 00:01:20.080 align:middle line:90%
I hope so.

00:01:20.080 --> 00:01:22.849 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --helps us understand
quantum physics, a very complex

00:01:22.849 --> 00:01:23.483 align:middle line:90%
topic.

00:01:23.483 --> 00:01:27.354 align:middle line:84%
So, let's talk a little bit
about how time is an illusion.

00:01:27.354 --> 00:01:29.823 align:middle line:84%
That's really the basis of
what we're talking about today.

00:01:29.823 --> 00:01:32.125 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Actually, what we're
really talking about today

00:01:32.125 --> 00:01:36.163 align:middle line:84%
is how you can become an
artist in your own life

00:01:36.163 --> 00:01:38.065 align:middle line:90%
and create your universe.

00:01:38.065 --> 00:01:39.265 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Create your universe.

00:01:39.265 --> 00:01:41.735 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: How to be an artist
creating your universe.

00:01:41.735 --> 00:01:45.104 align:middle line:84%
Because that is the real
trick to understanding

00:01:45.104 --> 00:01:46.807 align:middle line:84%
the nature of time,
space, matter,

00:01:46.807 --> 00:01:48.675 align:middle line:84%
all that stuff is
really understanding

00:01:48.675 --> 00:01:51.110 align:middle line:90%
who you really are.

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:53.646 align:middle line:84%
And most of us don't
know who we really are.

00:01:53.646 --> 00:01:56.149 align:middle line:90%
We think we are something else.

00:01:56.149 --> 00:01:56.750 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Right.

00:01:56.750 --> 00:01:58.685 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: And so,
what is the answer?

00:01:58.685 --> 00:02:00.821 align:middle line:84%
How do I become an artist
creating the universe?

00:02:00.821 --> 00:02:05.192 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is
learning to identify

00:02:05.192 --> 00:02:08.695 align:middle line:84%
with the dreaming
creator that you are.

00:02:08.695 --> 00:02:12.632 align:middle line:84%
And that's something
that sounds--

00:02:12.632 --> 00:02:16.303 align:middle line:84%
that sounds like science fiction
to me, Dr. Quantum, whatever.

00:02:16.303 --> 00:02:17.337 align:middle line:90%
How do I do that?

00:02:17.337 --> 00:02:19.206 align:middle line:90%
How do I go about doing that?

00:02:19.206 --> 00:02:22.209 align:middle line:84%
Well, we have to look for
some ancient teachings

00:02:22.209 --> 00:02:23.310 align:middle line:90%
to get some of this wisdom.

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:24.378 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That'll help us.

00:02:24.378 --> 00:02:25.512 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: That might help us.

00:02:25.512 --> 00:02:29.416 align:middle line:84%
And one of the ancient teachers
who first brought this out

00:02:29.416 --> 00:02:33.954 align:middle line:84%
to us all was somebody
that lived almost 2,600,

00:02:33.954 --> 00:02:38.191 align:middle line:84%
2,700 years ago he was
called Gautama, the Buddha.

00:02:38.191 --> 00:02:44.197 align:middle line:84%
And he said that the
trick, guys, bikinibu--

00:02:44.197 --> 00:02:45.531 align:middle line:90%
what'd he called his-- bhikkhus.

00:02:45.531 --> 00:02:48.035 align:middle line:90%
Bhikkus.

00:02:48.035 --> 00:02:51.271 align:middle line:84%
Priests, guys that are studying
under me, sitting at my feet.

00:02:51.271 --> 00:02:52.072 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Disciples.

00:02:52.072 --> 00:02:53.607 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: The trick--
disciples, right.

00:02:53.607 --> 00:02:57.344 align:middle line:84%
He says to know all things to
be like this, that what you're

00:02:57.344 --> 00:03:03.350 align:middle line:84%
seeing before you is a mirage,
a cloud floating in the air.

00:03:03.350 --> 00:03:05.419 align:middle line:90%
It's a phantom.

00:03:05.419 --> 00:03:09.856 align:middle line:84%
It's nothing really
real that you can really

00:03:09.856 --> 00:03:11.825 align:middle line:90%
put your feet on.

00:03:11.825 --> 00:03:14.061 align:middle line:90%
It has no essence.

00:03:14.061 --> 00:03:18.698 align:middle line:84%
It has nothing solid
that can be seen.

00:03:18.698 --> 00:03:23.270 align:middle line:84%
Know all things to be like
this, as the moon reflected

00:03:23.270 --> 00:03:28.008 align:middle line:84%
in a bright night
on a still stream.

00:03:28.008 --> 00:03:31.011 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So he was explaining
quantum physics way back then.

00:03:31.011 --> 00:03:32.746 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: He was
explaining the basis

00:03:32.746 --> 00:03:38.051 align:middle line:84%
of how one identifies
with the big dreamer

00:03:38.051 --> 00:03:42.656 align:middle line:84%
by understanding that all things
are really dreamlike rather

00:03:42.656 --> 00:03:45.859 align:middle line:90%
than solid reality.

00:03:45.859 --> 00:03:47.594 align:middle line:84%
He says know all
things to be like this,

00:03:47.594 --> 00:03:51.698 align:middle line:84%
to be something really
special, like an echo.

00:03:51.698 --> 00:03:54.668 align:middle line:84%
You hear an echo
reverberating in your ear,

00:03:54.668 --> 00:03:57.337 align:middle line:90%
but it's nothing spoken.

00:03:57.337 --> 00:03:59.139 align:middle line:90%
So this is the big trick.

00:03:59.139 --> 00:04:02.776 align:middle line:84%
As a magician might create
illusions of various things,

00:04:02.776 --> 00:04:05.846 align:middle line:84%
think of yourself
as the magician

00:04:05.846 --> 00:04:07.747 align:middle line:90%
creating the illusions.

00:04:07.747 --> 00:04:10.717 align:middle line:84%
You may be amazed at the
illusions you create.

00:04:10.717 --> 00:04:12.152 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: OK, so this
is how we start

00:04:12.152 --> 00:04:13.987 align:middle line:90%
to create our own universe.

00:04:13.987 --> 00:04:17.190 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: This is how we
create our own reality.

00:04:17.190 --> 00:04:19.192 align:middle line:84%
This is what the
Buddha's referring to.

00:04:19.192 --> 00:04:21.428 align:middle line:84%
But the first thing
you've got to refer to

00:04:21.428 --> 00:04:26.233 align:middle line:84%
is to understand that
everything is not as it seems.

00:04:26.233 --> 00:04:30.203 align:middle line:84%
Now, physicists
didn't quite catch on

00:04:30.203 --> 00:04:32.105 align:middle line:84%
with this at the
time of the Buddha.

00:04:32.105 --> 00:04:33.640 align:middle line:84%
Because there weren't
any physicists.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:34.474 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: At the time.

00:04:34.474 --> 00:04:35.509 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: --anyway.

00:04:35.509 --> 00:04:38.845 align:middle line:84%
In fact, around 1920 there
wasn't even maybe 300 of them

00:04:38.845 --> 00:04:41.181 align:middle line:90%
all in the whole earth.

00:04:41.181 --> 00:04:44.885 align:middle line:84%
So, by the time of
Werner Heisenberg, who

00:04:44.885 --> 00:04:48.088 align:middle line:84%
was a father of what's called
the uncertainty principle,

00:04:48.088 --> 00:04:49.756 align:middle line:90%
we begin to catch on.

00:04:49.756 --> 00:04:55.328 align:middle line:84%
And Heisenberg recognized that
what the physics was telling

00:04:55.328 --> 00:04:59.132 align:middle line:84%
him-- which is the birth
of quantum physics--

00:04:59.132 --> 00:05:03.837 align:middle line:84%
is that things are not as solid
as they appear, that there's

00:05:03.837 --> 00:05:08.608 align:middle line:84%
another realm of existence, what
he calls a middle realm, that's

00:05:08.608 --> 00:05:14.948 align:middle line:84%
between the conscious
mind and waking awareness

00:05:14.948 --> 00:05:20.387 align:middle line:84%
and something else,
something that's

00:05:20.387 --> 00:05:24.591 align:middle line:84%
between that conscious mind
and the so-called out there

00:05:24.591 --> 00:05:26.393 align:middle line:90%
world of physicality.

00:05:26.393 --> 00:05:28.695 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So there's something
between what we want--

00:05:28.695 --> 00:05:28.962 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Something between--

00:05:28.962 --> 00:05:29.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --and what is.

00:05:29.930 --> 00:05:30.463 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Yeah.

00:05:30.463 --> 00:05:32.465 align:middle line:84%
Something between
the material world

00:05:32.465 --> 00:05:34.935 align:middle line:90%
and the mind, which is created.

00:05:34.935 --> 00:05:38.305 align:middle line:84%
There is a middle
realm, something else,

00:05:38.305 --> 00:05:40.540 align:middle line:90%
a dreaming realm you might call.

00:05:40.540 --> 00:05:43.243 align:middle line:84%
In fact, I called it
the dreaming universe.

00:05:43.243 --> 00:05:44.778 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And that's
where we create.

00:05:44.778 --> 00:05:46.780 align:middle line:84%
That's where we get--
that's where the juice is.

00:05:46.780 --> 00:05:49.049 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: This is where
creation comes from.

00:05:49.049 --> 00:05:52.219 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's space
between the reality

00:05:52.219 --> 00:05:53.220 align:middle line:90%
and what we're creating.

00:05:53.220 --> 00:05:54.154 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Exactly.

00:05:54.154 --> 00:05:56.590 align:middle line:84%
And the elements of the
dream, the things that

00:05:56.590 --> 00:06:00.293 align:middle line:84%
come into this imaginal
realm of the dream world,

00:06:00.293 --> 00:06:04.097 align:middle line:84%
are the things that you've
worked with in new ways.

00:06:04.097 --> 00:06:07.367 align:middle line:84%
I mean, Freud was the first
to point out, there you are.

00:06:07.367 --> 00:06:09.436 align:middle line:84%
And you are in bed
with your mother.

00:06:09.436 --> 00:06:10.270 align:middle line:90%
Oh my God.

00:06:10.270 --> 00:06:11.671 align:middle line:90%
But she's only 20 years old.

00:06:11.671 --> 00:06:13.106 align:middle line:90%
How could I be doing that?

00:06:13.106 --> 00:06:15.942 align:middle line:84%
And all the kind
of weird Freudian

00:06:15.942 --> 00:06:17.143 align:middle line:90%
stuff that came out of there.

00:06:17.143 --> 00:06:18.812 align:middle line:84%
But Freud was
pointing to something

00:06:18.812 --> 00:06:22.616 align:middle line:84%
about the nature of dreams,
that time and space and matter

00:06:22.616 --> 00:06:24.551 align:middle line:90%
don't have the same meanings.

00:06:24.551 --> 00:06:26.486 align:middle line:84%
That thoughts and
feelings and sensations

00:06:26.486 --> 00:06:27.687 align:middle line:90%
don't have the same meanings.

00:06:27.687 --> 00:06:30.924 align:middle line:84%
But time, space, matter,
thoughts, and feelings

00:06:30.924 --> 00:06:34.394 align:middle line:84%
arise from this middle
realm, this invisible realm--

00:06:34.394 --> 00:06:35.428 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: From this realm--

00:06:35.428 --> 00:06:36.296 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Of existance.

00:06:36.296 --> 00:06:39.666 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --where we are often the
observer of that realm, right?

00:06:39.666 --> 00:06:40.734 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Exactly.

00:06:40.734 --> 00:06:41.334 align:middle line:90%
Exactly.

00:06:41.334 --> 00:06:44.504 align:middle line:84%
And we are observing in that
realm, although most of us--

00:06:44.504 --> 00:06:46.506 align:middle line:84%
many of us, for example,
sleep and we don't even

00:06:46.506 --> 00:06:47.874 align:middle line:90%
remember our dreams.

00:06:47.874 --> 00:06:49.175 align:middle line:90%
But some people do.

00:06:49.175 --> 00:06:51.378 align:middle line:84%
And some people wake
up in the dream.

00:06:51.378 --> 00:06:53.313 align:middle line:90%
We call that lucid dreaming.

00:06:53.313 --> 00:06:56.916 align:middle line:84%
And we have an experience
of the creative power

00:06:56.916 --> 00:07:00.053 align:middle line:84%
in lucid dreaming-- if
you begin to practice

00:07:00.053 --> 00:07:01.554 align:middle line:90%
that kind of a thing.

00:07:01.554 --> 00:07:03.056 align:middle line:90%
Anyway, that's the whole idea.

00:07:03.056 --> 00:07:04.324 align:middle line:90%
There's a story going on.

00:07:04.324 --> 00:07:07.394 align:middle line:84%
There's a story,
and your story is

00:07:07.394 --> 00:07:10.430 align:middle line:90%
made from this invisible realm.

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:13.933 align:middle line:84%
You're putting together
the ideas of a story

00:07:13.933 --> 00:07:18.238 align:middle line:84%
like braids that are being
twisted into storylines

00:07:18.238 --> 00:07:21.841 align:middle line:84%
of histories and stuff
that happened to you.

00:07:21.841 --> 00:07:25.745 align:middle line:84%
But the whole idea,
remember, is to identify

00:07:25.745 --> 00:07:29.249 align:middle line:84%
with the dreamer rather
than the dreamed.

00:07:29.249 --> 00:07:31.618 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Someone is asking--
one of our Facebook listeners

00:07:31.618 --> 00:07:34.721 align:middle line:84%
is asking-- Caroline-- when you
reference the observer in all

00:07:34.721 --> 00:07:36.056 align:middle line:90%
of us, do you mean awareness?

00:07:36.056 --> 00:07:37.457 align:middle line:90%
Do you--

00:07:37.457 --> 00:07:40.894 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Awareness is
something an observer does.

00:07:40.894 --> 00:07:44.931 align:middle line:84%
But the observer is
even beyond awareness.

00:07:44.931 --> 00:07:48.702 align:middle line:84%
The observer is something you
might call the super awareness

00:07:48.702 --> 00:07:50.203 align:middle line:90%
if you want to give it a name.

00:07:50.203 --> 00:07:53.640 align:middle line:84%
Or the mind of God if you want
to give it that kind of a name.

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:56.242 align:middle line:90%
It's awareness beyond awareness.

00:07:56.242 --> 00:07:57.977 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So it's a
universal awareness?

00:07:57.977 --> 00:08:00.580 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: It's something we call
the universal awareness, mind

00:08:00.580 --> 00:08:01.815 align:middle line:90%
of God.

00:08:01.815 --> 00:08:02.349 align:middle line:90%
It's--

00:08:02.349 --> 00:08:03.683 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Universal consciousness?

00:08:03.683 --> 00:08:06.286 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Universal consciousness.

00:08:06.286 --> 00:08:10.924 align:middle line:84%
Anytime you name it,
you sort of limit it.

00:08:10.924 --> 00:08:13.993 align:middle line:84%
We don't have the right
limits to apply to it yet.

00:08:13.993 --> 00:08:17.764 align:middle line:84%
So we can call it whatever
you wish at this point.

00:08:17.764 --> 00:08:18.331 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:08:18.331 --> 00:08:18.765 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:08:18.765 --> 00:08:20.633 align:middle line:84%
Holographic universe, as
we were talking about.

00:08:20.633 --> 00:08:21.735 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well that
we can get into.

00:08:21.735 --> 00:08:23.136 align:middle line:84%
Holographic universe,
I mean, what

00:08:23.136 --> 00:08:24.738 align:middle line:90%
the heck is going on there?

00:08:24.738 --> 00:08:27.674 align:middle line:84%
Well, in a larger
sense, in physics we

00:08:27.674 --> 00:08:30.643 align:middle line:84%
have found out that
quantum physics--

00:08:30.643 --> 00:08:32.445 align:middle line:84%
when you try to
put quantum physics

00:08:32.445 --> 00:08:36.182 align:middle line:84%
and Einstein's general
theory of relativity,

00:08:36.182 --> 00:08:39.953 align:middle line:84%
which was the attempt to bring
gravity into space and time,

00:08:39.953 --> 00:08:42.155 align:middle line:84%
when you try to
put those together

00:08:42.155 --> 00:08:44.958 align:middle line:84%
it's so hard to do
that nobody really

00:08:44.958 --> 00:08:47.360 align:middle line:84%
has figured out a way
to do it consistently.

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:49.028 align:middle line:90%
It's almost like it eludes us.

00:08:49.028 --> 00:08:50.563 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: To take
quantum physics and--

00:08:50.563 --> 00:08:52.599 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: And general
theory of relativity.

00:08:52.599 --> 00:08:53.400 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: --together.

00:08:53.400 --> 00:08:55.201 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Put gravity and
quantum physics together.

00:08:55.201 --> 00:08:56.336 align:middle line:90%
You can't seem to do it.

00:08:56.336 --> 00:08:58.138 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because one's
abstract and one's--

00:08:58.138 --> 00:08:59.672 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: One is
big and out there.

00:08:59.672 --> 00:08:59.939 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Concrete.

00:08:59.939 --> 00:09:01.941 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: And the other's small
and in here, so to speak.

00:09:01.941 --> 00:09:03.176 align:middle line:90%
And so it's very hard to do.

00:09:03.176 --> 00:09:06.446 align:middle line:84%
But physicists aren't
tired of giving up.

00:09:06.446 --> 00:09:08.548 align:middle line:84%
I mean they're not
tired of going on.

00:09:08.548 --> 00:09:09.349 align:middle line:90%
They don't give up.

00:09:09.349 --> 00:09:10.583 align:middle line:90%
They keep going on with this.

00:09:10.583 --> 00:09:12.852 align:middle line:84%
And they figured
out a new idea that

00:09:12.852 --> 00:09:15.155 align:middle line:84%
came when they
studied black holes.

00:09:15.155 --> 00:09:17.524 align:middle line:84%
They figured out-- a
black hole, by the way,

00:09:17.524 --> 00:09:21.961 align:middle line:84%
is when you have a
gravitationally collapsed star

00:09:21.961 --> 00:09:25.165 align:middle line:84%
that has so much mass that
it forms something called

00:09:25.165 --> 00:09:28.001 align:middle line:84%
a black hole, where space and
time around the black hole

00:09:28.001 --> 00:09:30.336 align:middle line:84%
get twisted in a
weird kind of way.

00:09:30.336 --> 00:09:36.443 align:middle line:84%
And something called a horizon--
spherical horizon-- forms

00:09:36.443 --> 00:09:38.678 align:middle line:90%
around the collapsed matter.

00:09:38.678 --> 00:09:42.148 align:middle line:84%
And on that horizon, space
and time get very weird.

00:09:42.148 --> 00:09:44.284 align:middle line:84%
And Stephen Hawking,
a physicist,

00:09:44.284 --> 00:09:48.988 align:middle line:84%
said you know, black
holes don't seem-- I mean,

00:09:48.988 --> 00:09:51.724 align:middle line:84%
if you throw something into a
black hole, it just disappears.

00:09:51.724 --> 00:09:53.426 align:middle line:84%
But in quantum
physics, we're always

00:09:53.426 --> 00:09:55.728 align:middle line:84%
worried about
things disappearing.

00:09:55.728 --> 00:09:58.231 align:middle line:84%
If they disappear, I
want them to come back.

00:09:58.231 --> 00:09:59.265 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah.

00:09:59.265 --> 00:10:01.734 align:middle line:84%
Because we've become
attached to reality.

00:10:01.734 --> 00:10:04.003 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: We don't
want things-- what

00:10:04.003 --> 00:10:05.572 align:middle line:90%
happens to the information?

00:10:05.572 --> 00:10:08.107 align:middle line:90%
Where does the information go?

00:10:08.107 --> 00:10:11.478 align:middle line:84%
And quantum physics don't
want to give up information.

00:10:11.478 --> 00:10:14.347 align:middle line:84%
And so, a physicist,
Jacob Bekenstein,

00:10:14.347 --> 00:10:17.517 align:middle line:84%
figured out that
the information gets

00:10:17.517 --> 00:10:20.186 align:middle line:84%
stored on the surfaces
of black holes.

00:10:20.186 --> 00:10:21.287 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Around that sphere?

00:10:21.287 --> 00:10:21.788 align:middle line:90%
Around--

00:10:21.788 --> 00:10:23.623 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Around this
collapsing stars.

00:10:23.623 --> 00:10:24.991 align:middle line:90%
And that got very weird.

00:10:24.991 --> 00:10:28.728 align:middle line:84%
Because if that's
true, then one could

00:10:28.728 --> 00:10:32.632 align:middle line:84%
map, from the information stored
on the black hole, everything

00:10:32.632 --> 00:10:35.602 align:middle line:84%
that was outside of
it that fell into it.

00:10:35.602 --> 00:10:38.705 align:middle line:84%
So, suddenly it became
possible-- physicists thought--

00:10:38.705 --> 00:10:44.711 align:middle line:84%
maybe everything in the universe
is on the surface of something.

00:10:44.711 --> 00:10:46.379 align:middle line:90%
Does it have to be a black hole?

00:10:46.379 --> 00:10:48.281 align:middle line:84%
And the answer
turned out to be it

00:10:48.281 --> 00:10:50.083 align:middle line:90%
doesn't have to be a black hole.

00:10:50.083 --> 00:10:53.686 align:middle line:84%
It can be any surface, anywhere,
where information could be

00:10:53.686 --> 00:10:57.724 align:middle line:84%
stored in such a way
that projected from that

00:10:57.724 --> 00:11:01.794 align:middle line:84%
information-- just like a movie
is projected from a camera--

00:11:01.794 --> 00:11:04.631 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So could also
happen within our own minds.

00:11:04.631 --> 00:11:06.499 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Not only our
own minds, but the thing

00:11:06.499 --> 00:11:08.801 align:middle line:84%
we're in right now, this
space we're in right now

00:11:08.801 --> 00:11:10.470 align:middle line:90%
is also being projected.

00:11:10.470 --> 00:11:12.772 align:middle line:84%
Even the third
dimension is being

00:11:12.772 --> 00:11:13.940 align:middle line:90%
projected from this surface.

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:18.077 align:middle line:84%
In other words, we ourselves
are being projected

00:11:18.077 --> 00:11:22.315 align:middle line:84%
from the surfaces
of something that's

00:11:22.315 --> 00:11:29.756 align:middle line:84%
where at infinity both forward
in time and backward in time

00:11:29.756 --> 00:11:31.190 align:middle line:90%
at the time of the Big Bang.

00:11:31.190 --> 00:11:32.358 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And now we're back--

00:11:32.358 --> 00:11:34.961 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: In other words,
