Hi, I'm Lisa Garr.

00:28:59.271 --> 00:29:02.074 align:middle line:84%
And my guest is Fred
Allan Wolfe, also known

00:29:02.074 --> 00:29:03.742 align:middle line:84%
as Dr. Quantum, like
I like to call him.

00:29:03.742 --> 00:29:05.544 align:middle line:84%
Because we're talking
about quantum physics

00:29:05.544 --> 00:29:07.746 align:middle line:84%
today, and bringing it
into our current reality,

00:29:07.746 --> 00:29:08.714 align:middle line:90%
whatever that might be.

00:29:08.714 --> 00:29:10.882 align:middle line:84%
Because it's all
an illusion anyway.

00:29:10.882 --> 00:29:14.186 align:middle line:84%
So, give me an example of
what this might look like.

00:29:14.186 --> 00:29:16.955 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, you
know the writers

00:29:16.955 --> 00:29:20.425 align:middle line:84%
that created a wonderful
television show a couple

00:29:20.425 --> 00:29:24.663 align:middle line:84%
years ago-- 20 years ago
or so-- called "Star Trek."

00:29:24.663 --> 00:29:26.465 align:middle line:84%
Gene Roddenberry's
great invention,

00:29:26.465 --> 00:29:29.534 align:middle line:84%
which led to "Star Trek:
The Next Generation," which

00:29:29.534 --> 00:29:31.803 align:middle line:90%
I thought-- I love "Star Trek."

00:29:31.803 --> 00:29:32.971 align:middle line:90%
I was a fan.

00:29:32.971 --> 00:29:33.872 align:middle line:90%
Bill Shatner, he's a--

00:29:33.872 --> 00:29:35.107 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Way ahead of
its time, that show.

00:29:35.107 --> 00:29:36.174 align:middle line:90%
That was a great show.

00:29:36.174 --> 00:29:37.643 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: But "The
Next Generation"

00:29:37.643 --> 00:29:41.847 align:middle line:84%
was really what I consider to
be the best that they've done.

00:29:41.847 --> 00:29:44.483 align:middle line:84%
And in that
particular show, they

00:29:44.483 --> 00:29:48.320 align:middle line:84%
had one episode that I thought
was really striking which

00:29:48.320 --> 00:29:53.025 align:middle line:84%
illustrates the notion that we
live in a holographic universe.

00:29:53.025 --> 00:30:00.732 align:middle line:84%
It was a show that was
entitled Ship in a Bottle.

00:30:00.732 --> 00:30:02.868 align:middle line:90%
You've seen ships in bottles.

00:30:02.868 --> 00:30:06.238 align:middle line:84%
And what happens in this
show is really interesting.

00:30:09.074 --> 00:30:11.677 align:middle line:84%
They have aboard
the Enterprise, they

00:30:11.677 --> 00:30:17.015 align:middle line:90%
have a room called the holoroom.

00:30:17.015 --> 00:30:19.785 align:middle line:84%
The holoroom is a
room with just walls,

00:30:19.785 --> 00:30:22.387 align:middle line:84%
but it's capable of
generating holographic images.

00:30:22.387 --> 00:30:23.388 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I remember this.

00:30:23.388 --> 00:30:23.722 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:30:23.722 --> 00:30:24.222 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Yes.

00:30:24.222 --> 00:30:26.758 align:middle line:84%
And these holographic
images are so

00:30:26.758 --> 00:30:29.628 align:middle line:84%
real that they become
three dimensional

00:30:29.628 --> 00:30:31.329 align:middle line:90%
in the middle of the room.

00:30:31.329 --> 00:30:35.033 align:middle line:84%
And so that people can
walk into the holoroom.

00:30:35.033 --> 00:30:37.969 align:middle line:84%
And when they walked
into this holoroom

00:30:37.969 --> 00:30:42.674 align:middle line:84%
with characters that are being
created by the holographic room

00:30:42.674 --> 00:30:44.976 align:middle line:84%
itself, they can
interact with them.

00:30:44.976 --> 00:30:47.079 align:middle line:84%
And the room-- the
characters interact

00:30:47.079 --> 00:30:50.482 align:middle line:84%
with the so-called real
characters or the real ship

00:30:50.482 --> 00:30:50.982 align:middle line:90%
members.

00:30:50.982 --> 00:30:53.952 align:middle line:84%
Well, one day, this
character emerges

00:30:53.952 --> 00:30:57.189 align:middle line:84%
who calls himself Dr.
Moriarty, from Sherlock Holmes,

00:30:57.189 --> 00:31:00.926 align:middle line:84%
probably because
Data was dreaming up

00:31:00.926 --> 00:31:02.794 align:middle line:90%
stories about Sherlock Holmes.

00:31:02.794 --> 00:31:11.203 align:middle line:84%
And Dr. M appears and says,
I think, therefore I am.

00:31:11.203 --> 00:31:13.505 align:middle line:84%
I am not going to
risk-- I'm not going

00:31:13.505 --> 00:31:16.408 align:middle line:84%
to stay the rest of my
life in this holoroom.

00:31:16.408 --> 00:31:17.776 align:middle line:90%
I have a memory.

00:31:17.776 --> 00:31:20.846 align:middle line:84%
Something that Data must
have done to change a program

00:31:20.846 --> 00:31:25.016 align:middle line:84%
to give this character the
ability to think what he has

00:31:25.016 --> 00:31:26.051 align:middle line:90%
is a memory.

00:31:26.051 --> 00:31:28.653 align:middle line:84%
I have a memory,
and I know that I

00:31:28.653 --> 00:31:31.356 align:middle line:84%
am Dr. Moriarty in
a holographic room.

00:31:31.356 --> 00:31:34.192 align:middle line:84%
And I'm going to get out
of this holographic room.

00:31:34.192 --> 00:31:36.495 align:middle line:84%
Well, the holographic room
looks something like this.

00:31:36.495 --> 00:31:42.367 align:middle line:84%
It's a big empty lattice of
possibility with a doorway.

00:31:42.367 --> 00:31:44.970 align:middle line:90%
And so, Dr. Moriarty says, no.

00:31:44.970 --> 00:31:47.005 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to stay
in this room anymore.

00:31:47.005 --> 00:31:48.573 align:middle line:90%
I don't want to be here anymore.

00:31:48.573 --> 00:31:51.610 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to walk out of
the holoroom entirely.

00:31:51.610 --> 00:31:54.146 align:middle line:84%
And everybody says,
you can't do that.

00:31:54.146 --> 00:31:56.648 align:middle line:84%
It's against holographic
principal physics.

00:31:56.648 --> 00:31:59.518 align:middle line:84%
There's no way that a
hologram can walk out

00:31:59.518 --> 00:32:00.886 align:middle line:90%
of the holograph room.

00:32:00.886 --> 00:32:01.853 align:middle line:90%
You just can't do that.

00:32:01.853 --> 00:32:04.222 align:middle line:90%
You can't exist out there.

00:32:04.222 --> 00:32:05.624 align:middle line:90%
That's nonexistence.

00:32:05.624 --> 00:32:07.459 align:middle line:90%
There is no such thing.

00:32:07.459 --> 00:32:09.728 align:middle line:90%
And Dr. Moriarty says no.

00:32:09.728 --> 00:32:12.330 align:middle line:84%
He says, I think,
therefore I am.

00:32:12.330 --> 00:32:13.865 align:middle line:90%
And I'm going to do that.

00:32:13.865 --> 00:32:16.768 align:middle line:90%
So Dr. Moriarty says open.

00:32:16.768 --> 00:32:17.869 align:middle line:90%
The doors open.

00:32:17.869 --> 00:32:20.705 align:middle line:84%
And he walks out
into the spaceship.

00:32:20.705 --> 00:32:23.308 align:middle line:84%
And the rest of the
crew says, oh my God.

00:32:23.308 --> 00:32:24.342 align:middle line:90%
He's done it.

00:32:24.342 --> 00:32:26.444 align:middle line:84%
He's created himself
outside of the holoroom.

00:32:26.444 --> 00:32:27.479 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: He's become real.

00:32:27.479 --> 00:32:28.947 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: How-- He's become real.

00:32:28.947 --> 00:32:30.215 align:middle line:90%
How did he do that?

00:32:30.215 --> 00:32:32.384 align:middle line:90%
What is going on here?

00:32:32.384 --> 00:32:35.420 align:middle line:90%
Well, we're all wondering, too.

00:32:35.420 --> 00:32:38.256 align:middle line:84%
How is it possible
that this character

00:32:38.256 --> 00:32:40.759 align:middle line:84%
could have suddenly emerged
and started walking around

00:32:40.759 --> 00:32:42.594 align:middle line:84%
the ship doing all
kinds of mischief

00:32:42.594 --> 00:32:45.497 align:middle line:84%
like they usually do in
these kind of stories.

00:32:45.497 --> 00:32:52.204 align:middle line:84%
Well, it turns out that this
character, Dr. Moriarty,

00:32:52.204 --> 00:32:56.741 align:middle line:90%
really never left the holo room.

00:32:56.741 --> 00:33:00.412 align:middle line:84%
But being clever, and
learning the creative process,

00:33:00.412 --> 00:33:03.915 align:middle line:84%
and learning to identify with
the creator process-- which

00:33:03.915 --> 00:33:07.519 align:middle line:84%
in this case was Data's fertile
mind-- I'm kind of making this

00:33:07.519 --> 00:33:08.353 align:middle line:90%
up as I go along.

00:33:08.353 --> 00:33:12.691 align:middle line:84%
It may not be exactly
the way the stories went.

00:33:12.691 --> 00:33:19.364 align:middle line:84%
He created a holoroom within the
holoroom, within the holoroom,

00:33:19.364 --> 00:33:21.499 align:middle line:84%
within the holoroom,
within the holoroom.

00:33:21.499 --> 00:33:25.971 align:middle line:84%
So that even though he appeared
to walk out of the holoroom

00:33:25.971 --> 00:33:29.608 align:middle line:84%
into the spaceship, he never
had really left the real quote,

00:33:29.608 --> 00:33:31.276 align:middle line:90%
unquote holoroom.

00:33:31.276 --> 00:33:33.044 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Are you
applying this at home?

00:33:33.044 --> 00:33:33.545 align:middle line:90%
Really?

00:33:33.545 --> 00:33:35.413 align:middle line:84%
I mean, think about
this in your own life,

00:33:35.413 --> 00:33:39.150 align:middle line:84%
how we are creating an image,
an illusion of ourselves.

00:33:39.150 --> 00:33:41.119 align:middle line:90%
Are we really real?

00:33:41.119 --> 00:33:41.953 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Right.

00:33:41.953 --> 00:33:47.392 align:middle line:84%
Right, and Dr. Moriarty
thinks that he is now real,

00:33:47.392 --> 00:33:50.295 align:middle line:84%
and he wants to
explore the universe.

00:33:50.295 --> 00:33:53.865 align:middle line:84%
So Picard, the captain,
thinks of a very clever way

00:33:53.865 --> 00:33:54.799 align:middle line:90%
to do this.

00:33:54.799 --> 00:33:57.736 align:middle line:84%
He programs the
whole-- once they

00:33:57.736 --> 00:34:01.206 align:middle line:84%
catch on to what's
going on-- the crew

00:34:01.206 --> 00:34:06.845 align:middle line:84%
catches-- or takes
the software that's

00:34:06.845 --> 00:34:11.116 align:middle line:84%
generating this whole thing
and encapsulate it inside

00:34:11.116 --> 00:34:14.619 align:middle line:84%
of a cube, together
with images of the crew

00:34:14.619 --> 00:34:18.322 align:middle line:84%
so that Dr. Moriarty
never really catches on

00:34:18.322 --> 00:34:20.692 align:middle line:84%
that he's part of a
holographic computer program.

00:34:20.692 --> 00:34:21.326 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Got it.

00:34:21.326 --> 00:34:21.659 align:middle line:90%
Got it.

00:34:21.659 --> 00:34:22.159 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:34:22.159 --> 00:34:25.297 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: And so then, the
crew member holding up a cube

00:34:25.297 --> 00:34:29.801 align:middle line:84%
containing the whole kit and
caboodle with Dr. Moriarty,

00:34:29.801 --> 00:34:32.437 align:middle line:84%
and Picard, and the
ship, and even visions

00:34:32.437 --> 00:34:35.774 align:middle line:84%
of the whole universe--
holding up the cube,

00:34:35.774 --> 00:34:40.946 align:middle line:84%
wondering, wait a minute,
what is really going on here?

00:34:40.946 --> 00:34:44.815 align:middle line:90%
Is this really the way it is?

00:34:44.815 --> 00:34:49.020 align:middle line:84%
Or am I, myself, a
projection from some bigger

00:34:49.020 --> 00:34:51.389 align:middle line:84%
holographic room that
I don't know about.

00:34:51.389 --> 00:34:52.623 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Which is what we are.

00:34:52.623 --> 00:34:56.027 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Which is what
the current physics says.

00:34:56.027 --> 00:34:56.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That we are.

00:34:56.860 --> 00:35:00.865 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: So, we are actually
like this story that

00:35:00.865 --> 00:35:04.502 align:middle line:84%
is projected from
some bigger holoroom.

00:35:04.502 --> 00:35:07.605 align:middle line:84%
In this case, the
holoroom are the surfaces

00:35:07.605 --> 00:35:11.409 align:middle line:84%
at the beginning and ending
of time, where the mind of God

00:35:11.409 --> 00:35:13.378 align:middle line:90%
is fertile and existing.

00:35:13.378 --> 00:35:17.916 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So, we can really
dream up our own reality.

00:35:17.916 --> 00:35:19.751 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: If we can
imagine this, we

00:35:19.751 --> 00:35:21.886 align:middle line:90%
can begin to identify with it.

00:35:21.886 --> 00:35:25.790 align:middle line:84%
And you actually get
a chance to do it.

00:35:25.790 --> 00:35:26.891 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: In what way?

00:35:26.891 --> 00:35:28.927 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: When you die.

00:35:28.927 --> 00:35:30.195 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Isn't it a little late?

00:35:30.195 --> 00:35:33.965 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: You also get a chance
to do it when you're born.

00:35:33.965 --> 00:35:38.370 align:middle line:84%
You get glimpses of who you
really are at those moments.

00:35:38.370 --> 00:35:39.938 align:middle line:90%
But very quickly--

00:35:39.938 --> 00:35:40.872 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Why don't we--

00:35:40.872 --> 00:35:42.040 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: --before and after--

00:35:42.040 --> 00:35:44.042 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --experience
that in our daily lives?

00:35:44.042 --> 00:35:45.710 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: That's a good question.

00:35:45.710 --> 00:35:49.848 align:middle line:84%
And the answer is that
you can identify with it,

00:35:49.848 --> 00:35:54.953 align:middle line:84%
but you have to realize
that being holographic

00:35:54.953 --> 00:35:58.423 align:middle line:84%
doesn't necessarily
make the world have

00:35:58.423 --> 00:36:00.158 align:middle line:90%
any difficulties with it.

00:36:00.158 --> 00:36:02.527 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing
hard to push around.

00:36:02.527 --> 00:36:04.696 align:middle line:84%
There's no matter
to push around.

00:36:04.696 --> 00:36:07.065 align:middle line:84%
There's no striving
for anything.

00:36:07.065 --> 00:36:09.134 align:middle line:90%
There's no worthwhileness.

00:36:09.134 --> 00:36:11.803 align:middle line:90%
Everything's, so to speak, free.

00:36:11.803 --> 00:36:14.372 align:middle line:84%
And while that sounds wonderful
for maybe the first four

00:36:14.372 --> 00:36:17.008 align:middle line:84%
or five days of that kind
of, oh everything's free,

00:36:17.008 --> 00:36:18.943 align:middle line:84%
I can have whatever I
want, after a while,

00:36:18.943 --> 00:36:20.512 align:middle line:84%
when you realize you
can have anything

00:36:20.512 --> 00:36:23.348 align:middle line:84%
you want whenever you need
it, or whenever you want it,

00:36:23.348 --> 00:36:24.849 align:middle line:90%
you don't want anything anymore.

00:36:24.849 --> 00:36:25.550 align:middle line:84%
What you want is the
opposite of that.

00:36:25.550 --> 00:36:27.385 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Exactly how
long would that take?

00:36:27.385 --> 00:36:28.386 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Oh, four or five days.

00:36:28.386 --> 00:36:29.154 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh, really?

00:36:29.154 --> 00:36:29.788 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: That's about it.

00:36:29.788 --> 00:36:30.055 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Really?

00:36:30.055 --> 00:36:31.122 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Four or five
days of getting anything

00:36:31.122 --> 00:36:33.458 align:middle line:84%
you want, any time you
want it, it's about enough.

00:36:33.458 --> 00:36:35.093 align:middle line:84%
You'd be bored after
four or five days.

00:36:35.093 --> 00:36:37.362 align:middle line:84%
Some people are bored after
that after a couple of minutes.

00:36:37.362 --> 00:36:38.730 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well,
that's interesting.

00:36:38.730 --> 00:36:41.566 align:middle line:84%
Because I would want
to have other people

00:36:41.566 --> 00:36:44.736 align:middle line:84%
experience it with me, or
share that with other people,

00:36:44.736 --> 00:36:47.806 align:middle line:84%
or in some way pay it forward
or something like that.

00:36:47.806 --> 00:36:48.807 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, that's true.

00:36:48.807 --> 00:36:49.641 align:middle line:90%
That's true.

00:36:49.641 --> 00:36:51.576 align:middle line:84%
It would be pretty
lonely, wouldn't it?

00:36:51.576 --> 00:36:54.579 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: It could turn out to be
a kind of a lonely experience.

00:36:54.579 --> 00:36:55.747 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because we want
to share it with everyone.

00:36:55.747 --> 00:36:56.314 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: The being all one.

00:36:56.314 --> 00:36:58.083 align:middle line:84%
For example, let's
say you realize now

00:36:58.083 --> 00:37:00.852 align:middle line:84%
that you're everything
there is, everything

00:37:00.852 --> 00:37:03.588 align:middle line:84%
that was, everything
that will be.

00:37:03.588 --> 00:37:07.759 align:middle line:84%
In fact was, will be,
is have no meaning,

00:37:07.759 --> 00:37:10.361 align:middle line:84%
because you're beyond
space and time.

00:37:10.361 --> 00:37:14.466 align:middle line:84%
So you are all
there is eternally.

00:37:14.466 --> 00:37:17.235 align:middle line:84%
How would you feel being
all there is forever

00:37:17.235 --> 00:37:22.640 align:middle line:84%
and ever and ever and ever
and ever and never, ever

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:26.644 align:middle line:84%
having anything other
than eternal existence

00:37:26.644 --> 00:37:30.849 align:middle line:84%
forever and ever, being able
to do whatever you want.

00:37:30.849 --> 00:37:34.619 align:middle line:84%
Eventually, you start to think
about creating limitation.

00:37:34.619 --> 00:37:35.453 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Interesting.

00:37:35.453 --> 00:37:38.957 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, to-- I mean, think about
that at home and then breathe.

00:37:38.957 --> 00:37:42.193 align:middle line:84%
Because that is a vast,
vast, vast concept.

00:37:42.193 --> 00:37:45.396 align:middle line:84%
And then, you would think
about where are the boundaries.

00:37:45.396 --> 00:37:46.498 align:middle line:90%
Just like a little kid--

00:37:46.498 --> 00:37:46.764 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: That's exactly right.

00:37:46.764 --> 00:37:48.933 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: --wondering where--
they come into the world

00:37:48.933 --> 00:37:50.535 align:middle line:84%
and the universe
is a blur to them.

00:37:50.535 --> 00:37:53.171 align:middle line:84%
And they look for where they can
bump up against it to find out

00:37:53.171 --> 00:37:54.372 align:middle line:90%
how they are in relationship.

00:37:54.372 --> 00:37:55.440 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Exactly, exactly.

00:37:55.440 --> 00:37:57.108 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Absolutely
that would be there.

00:37:57.108 --> 00:37:58.710 align:middle line:84%
So, we are a live
show here, and we're

00:37:58.710 --> 00:38:00.145 align:middle line:84%
encouraging you to
communicate with us

00:38:00.145 --> 00:38:01.246 align:middle line:90%
via Facebook and Twitter.

