And we have some questions
coming in here, too.

00:38:04.549 --> 00:38:06.351 align:middle line:90%
Wow.

00:38:06.351 --> 00:38:07.719 align:middle line:84%
Jan asked about
what do you think

00:38:07.719 --> 00:38:09.521 align:middle line:90%
about the law of attraction.

00:38:09.521 --> 00:38:12.590 align:middle line:84%
What do you think about that in
quantum physics perspectives?

00:38:12.590 --> 00:38:15.093 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, I've said a lot
about that on my web page.

00:38:15.093 --> 00:38:17.495 align:middle line:84%
You can read a longer
answer than I'm

00:38:17.495 --> 00:38:18.530 align:middle line:90%
going to give right here.

00:38:18.530 --> 00:38:20.999 align:middle line:84%
But the law of
attraction is really

00:38:20.999 --> 00:38:27.305 align:middle line:84%
a kind of more of a
sales kind of a thing.

00:38:27.305 --> 00:38:30.441 align:middle line:84%
It's to get people outside of
their normal kind of thinking.

00:38:30.441 --> 00:38:33.545 align:middle line:84%
But the law of
attraction in physics

00:38:33.545 --> 00:38:37.315 align:middle line:84%
is that opposites attract,
not likes attract.

00:38:37.315 --> 00:38:39.417 align:middle line:90%
So--

00:38:39.417 --> 00:38:40.351 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Explain.

00:38:40.351 --> 00:38:43.555 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, a positive
electrical charge

00:38:43.555 --> 00:38:46.324 align:middle line:84%
does not attract another
positive electrical charge.

00:38:46.324 --> 00:38:48.193 align:middle line:90%
In fact, it repels it.

00:38:48.193 --> 00:38:50.862 align:middle line:90%
So likes repel each other.

00:38:50.862 --> 00:38:52.931 align:middle line:84%
A positive electrical
charge will

00:38:52.931 --> 00:38:55.099 align:middle line:84%
attract a negative
electrical charge.

00:38:55.099 --> 00:38:56.634 align:middle line:84%
And if it didn't do
that, we wouldn't

00:38:56.634 --> 00:38:59.270 align:middle line:84%
have electricity nor even
the existence of atoms.

00:38:59.270 --> 00:39:00.838 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That explains
a lot of things.

00:39:00.838 --> 00:39:01.506 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:39:01.506 --> 00:39:04.108 align:middle line:84%
So in relationships that
explains that, but what about--

00:39:04.108 --> 00:39:05.510 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: And often
in relationships

00:39:05.510 --> 00:39:07.045 align:middle line:84%
we find a similar
of kind of thing,

00:39:07.045 --> 00:39:09.547 align:middle line:90%
opposites attracting each other.

00:39:09.547 --> 00:39:10.048 align:middle line:90%
And so--

00:39:10.048 --> 00:39:11.115 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What about goals?

00:39:11.115 --> 00:39:12.450 align:middle line:90%
When you want to attract goals?

00:39:12.450 --> 00:39:14.752 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well,
rather than thinking

00:39:14.752 --> 00:39:17.655 align:middle line:84%
about attracting
something to yourself,

00:39:17.655 --> 00:39:22.060 align:middle line:84%
think about what it is that
you can give of yourself

00:39:22.060 --> 00:39:24.429 align:middle line:84%
which will make
your life better.

00:39:24.429 --> 00:39:27.165 align:middle line:84%
Rather than bringing
something in,

00:39:27.165 --> 00:39:30.235 align:middle line:84%
what can you push out
from yourself that'll

00:39:30.235 --> 00:39:32.437 align:middle line:84%
make your life more
interesting and better.

00:39:32.437 --> 00:39:35.707 align:middle line:84%
Because it's really in the
giving that the greater joy

00:39:35.707 --> 00:39:37.108 align:middle line:90%
is achieved.

00:39:37.108 --> 00:39:39.711 align:middle line:84%
Spiritual teachers have
been telling this for years,

00:39:39.711 --> 00:39:41.479 align:middle line:84%
but until you actually
start doing it,

00:39:41.479 --> 00:39:42.780 align:middle line:84%
you're not going to
know what I'm talking.

00:39:42.780 --> 00:39:45.116 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If we could all do
that on a quantum level,

00:39:45.116 --> 00:39:46.951 align:middle line:84%
this would be a different
place, absolutely.

00:39:46.951 --> 00:39:49.053 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Well, we're doing it.

00:39:49.053 --> 00:39:51.322 align:middle line:84%
I mean, we're getting
more people doing it.

00:39:51.322 --> 00:39:53.224 align:middle line:84%
And people are asking
the right questions.

00:39:53.224 --> 00:39:55.760 align:middle line:90%
It is going on.

00:39:55.760 --> 00:39:56.961 align:middle line:90%
And it's going to continue.

00:39:56.961 --> 00:39:58.096 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's a good news.

00:39:58.096 --> 00:40:00.398 align:middle line:84%
All right, so our
slide that we have here

00:40:00.398 --> 00:40:03.635 align:middle line:84%
is about the teachings
of Chuang Tzu.

00:40:03.635 --> 00:40:04.535 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: That's right.

00:40:07.071 --> 00:40:08.573 align:middle line:84%
In the ancient--
you know, I've just

00:40:08.573 --> 00:40:10.608 align:middle line:84%
taken you through the
"Star Trek" story.

00:40:10.608 --> 00:40:14.612 align:middle line:84%
But Chuang Tzu was
a great philosopher.

00:40:14.612 --> 00:40:16.614 align:middle line:90%
And he wrote these words.

00:40:16.614 --> 00:40:19.684 align:middle line:84%
He says that someday will
come this Great Awakening.

00:40:19.684 --> 00:40:22.587 align:middle line:84%
And we're all going
to realize something,

00:40:22.587 --> 00:40:28.426 align:middle line:84%
that life is no
more than a dream.

00:40:28.426 --> 00:40:32.830 align:middle line:84%
Yet the foolish
will go on thinking

00:40:32.830 --> 00:40:37.535 align:middle line:84%
that they are awake, and that
everything-- this is real.

00:40:37.535 --> 00:40:38.903 align:middle line:90%
This is reality, darn it.

00:40:38.903 --> 00:40:40.605 align:middle line:90%
This is the way it is.

00:40:40.605 --> 00:40:43.941 align:middle line:84%
And surveying the
panorama of all the things

00:40:43.941 --> 00:40:48.880 align:middle line:84%
that make up our lives, they
will call this one a prince.

00:40:48.880 --> 00:40:50.615 align:middle line:84%
And that one over
there, well he's

00:40:50.615 --> 00:40:52.884 align:middle line:90%
richer than, gosh, anybody else.

00:40:52.884 --> 00:40:53.651 align:middle line:90%
And that's a slob.

00:40:53.651 --> 00:40:55.353 align:middle line:90%
He's poorer than anybody else.

00:40:55.353 --> 00:40:56.254 align:middle line:90%
And he's a nothing.

00:40:56.254 --> 00:40:57.288 align:middle line:90%
He's a something.

00:40:57.288 --> 00:40:58.156 align:middle line:84%
I want to be with
the somethings,

00:40:58.156 --> 00:40:59.057 align:middle line:90%
not with the nothings.

00:40:59.057 --> 00:41:01.726 align:middle line:84%
And all that kind of stuff
that we keep going through.

00:41:01.726 --> 00:41:05.997 align:middle line:84%
And all that kind of thinking,
and thinking and talking,

00:41:05.997 --> 00:41:09.500 align:middle line:84%
all that is part of just
no more than a dream.

00:41:09.500 --> 00:41:16.107 align:middle line:84%
And I, who say this, Chuang
Tzu said, I who say this,

00:41:16.107 --> 00:41:17.742 align:middle line:90%
I am also a dream.

00:41:17.742 --> 00:41:20.812 align:middle line:90%
I, too, am a dream.

00:41:20.812 --> 00:41:24.782 align:middle line:84%
Is this a butterfly dreaming
he's Chuang Tzu or Chuang

00:41:24.782 --> 00:41:26.451 align:middle line:90%
Tzu dreaming he's a butterfly?

00:41:26.451 --> 00:41:28.052 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is it the
caterpillar dreaming

00:41:28.052 --> 00:41:29.921 align:middle line:84%
that he's a butterfly or
the butterfly dreaming

00:41:29.921 --> 00:41:30.321 align:middle line:90%
he's a caterpillar?

00:41:30.321 --> 00:41:32.090 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: The caterpillar
dreams he's a butterfly.

00:41:32.090 --> 00:41:32.924 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yeah, he does.

00:41:32.924 --> 00:41:34.192 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Otherwise he
wouldn't go through all that.

00:41:34.192 --> 00:41:36.060 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: He has the DNA
strand of a butterfly.

00:41:36.060 --> 00:41:37.228 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: He's got the desire.

00:41:37.228 --> 00:41:38.763 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yeah, he
does, absolutely.

00:41:38.763 --> 00:41:39.831 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Because it
takes a lot of work

00:41:39.831 --> 00:41:41.733 align:middle line:84%
to make yourself
into a caterpillar.

00:41:41.733 --> 00:41:42.567 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: One of our--

00:41:42.567 --> 00:41:44.001 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: I mean,
into a butterfly.

00:41:44.001 --> 00:41:47.205 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, absolutely,
takes a lot of work.

00:41:47.205 --> 00:41:49.640 align:middle line:84%
Ryan is asking
what about deja vu?

00:41:49.640 --> 00:41:51.542 align:middle line:84%
Is that a collision
of realities?

00:41:51.542 --> 00:41:53.811 align:middle line:84%
And parallel universes,
another-- Patrick

00:41:53.811 --> 00:41:56.614 align:middle line:84%
is also asking how do we access
these parallel universes?

00:41:56.614 --> 00:41:57.215 align:middle line:90%
Do they exist?

00:41:57.215 --> 00:41:59.050 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, parallel
realities and deja vu

00:41:59.050 --> 00:42:02.420 align:middle line:84%
are really similar questions
in a certain sense.

00:42:02.420 --> 00:42:05.390 align:middle line:84%
When you have a deja vu
experience, what you're

00:42:05.390 --> 00:42:10.995 align:middle line:84%
experiencing is, in a certain
sense, what at the time

00:42:10.995 --> 00:42:14.966 align:middle line:84%
was about to be and
you're reminded of that.

00:42:14.966 --> 00:42:21.005 align:middle line:84%
It's really something which lets
you know that you've seen this

00:42:21.005 --> 00:42:24.175 align:middle line:84%
before, in a parallel
world, possibly.

00:42:24.175 --> 00:42:27.578 align:middle line:84%
So that's what the deja
vu experience is about.

00:42:27.578 --> 00:42:28.246 align:middle line:90%
Oh, yeah.

00:42:28.246 --> 00:42:30.581 align:middle line:84%
I remember having this
conversation before.

00:42:30.581 --> 00:42:34.051 align:middle line:84%
Well, indeed, you may
have had that conversation

00:42:34.051 --> 00:42:39.023 align:middle line:84%
before in your parallel world
self or your otherworldly self.

00:42:39.023 --> 00:42:40.758 align:middle line:84%
So deja vu is a kind
of reminder of that.

00:42:40.758 --> 00:42:42.193 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Do you
really believe that?

00:42:42.193 --> 00:42:42.693 align:middle line:90%
That that--

00:42:42.693 --> 00:42:44.228 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Yeah, well,
because there's

00:42:44.228 --> 00:42:47.432 align:middle line:84%
no reason why we don't
have these parallel worlds.

00:42:47.432 --> 00:42:48.766 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What makes you say that?

00:42:48.766 --> 00:42:49.100 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: What?

00:42:49.100 --> 00:42:51.035 align:middle line:84%
Because that's what quantum
physics is telling us.

00:42:51.035 --> 00:42:52.670 align:middle line:84%
I mean, whether I
believe it or not,

00:42:52.670 --> 00:42:54.939 align:middle line:84%
it's just that
quantum physics works

00:42:54.939 --> 00:42:56.107 align:middle line:90%
to explain a lot of stuff.

00:42:56.107 --> 00:42:58.276 align:middle line:84%
And it does say there
are parallel worlds.

00:42:58.276 --> 00:43:02.013 align:middle line:84%
So whether we like it or
not, it seems to be there.

00:43:02.013 --> 00:43:04.215 align:middle line:84%
There are two kinds
of vu experiences.

00:43:04.215 --> 00:43:08.252 align:middle line:84%
There's deja vu and
there's jamais vu.

00:43:08.252 --> 00:43:12.390 align:middle line:84%
And jamais vu is never having
had this experience before.

00:43:12.390 --> 00:43:15.793 align:middle line:84%
Of the two, I prefer jamais
vu, because jamais vu

00:43:15.793 --> 00:43:16.794 align:middle line:90%
is really exciting.

00:43:16.794 --> 00:43:17.261 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Experiencing
it for the first time.

00:43:17.261 --> 00:43:19.397 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: I've never
done this before, wow.

00:43:19.397 --> 00:43:22.066 align:middle line:84%
Deja vu, well, everything,
in a way, is deja vu.

00:43:22.066 --> 00:43:25.236 align:middle line:84%
If things are so deja vu that
you've done them over and over

00:43:25.236 --> 00:43:28.873 align:middle line:84%
again, they get--
it becomes jamais vu

00:43:28.873 --> 00:43:30.508 align:middle line:84%
that you may have
the experience of not

00:43:30.508 --> 00:43:32.610 align:middle line:90%
having had that experience.

00:43:32.610 --> 00:43:35.580 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You said something that
I don't want you to gloss over.

00:43:35.580 --> 00:43:37.281 align:middle line:84%
You said that quantum
physics really

00:43:37.281 --> 00:43:39.250 align:middle line:90%
does explain parallel universes.

00:43:39.250 --> 00:43:40.351 align:middle line:90%
My mind is hooked on--

00:43:40.351 --> 00:43:41.552 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: They're necessary.

00:43:41.552 --> 00:43:42.220 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Explain.

00:43:42.220 --> 00:43:43.454 align:middle line:90%
I want to know more about that.

00:43:43.454 --> 00:43:44.422 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, because
quantum physics

00:43:44.422 --> 00:43:46.491 align:middle line:84%
says there are many--
remember the bubbles?

00:43:46.491 --> 00:43:49.327 align:middle line:84%
There are many
possible-- each bubble

00:43:49.327 --> 00:43:51.929 align:middle line:90%
is a possible world, a universe.

00:43:51.929 --> 00:43:55.233 align:middle line:84%
And quantum physics
tells us that there

00:43:55.233 --> 00:43:58.269 align:middle line:84%
are many possibilities
that must coexist,

00:43:58.269 --> 00:44:00.271 align:middle line:84%
that we don't just
have one or the other;

00:44:00.271 --> 00:44:02.507 align:middle line:90%
we get one and the other.

00:44:02.507 --> 00:44:05.776 align:middle line:84%
So parallel worlds are just a
different possible storylines

00:44:05.776 --> 00:44:08.145 align:middle line:84%
which can develop through
those bubbles of possibility.

00:44:08.145 --> 00:44:10.147 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So let me bring
this into practical use.

00:44:10.147 --> 00:44:13.885 align:middle line:84%
So, if we want to try to
determine the outcome.

00:44:13.885 --> 00:44:16.954 align:middle line:84%
Say you're in a lawsuit, or
you want the positive truth

00:44:16.954 --> 00:44:17.588 align:middle line:90%
to come out.

00:44:17.588 --> 00:44:20.858 align:middle line:84%
Can you access the parallel
universe for the positive truth

00:44:20.858 --> 00:44:23.828 align:middle line:90%
to come out of some situation?

00:44:23.828 --> 00:44:24.829 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: You can.

00:44:24.829 --> 00:44:28.633 align:middle line:84%
And sometimes it's not very
likely that it'll happen.

00:44:28.633 --> 00:44:31.135 align:middle line:84%
It depends on a lot of
factors, which may have more

00:44:31.135 --> 00:44:36.707 align:middle line:84%
to do with your own
personal you-ness.

00:44:36.707 --> 00:44:40.344 align:middle line:84%
The big trick in identifying
with the big dreamer

00:44:40.344 --> 00:44:42.980 align:middle line:84%
is to remember who
you really are.

00:44:42.980 --> 00:44:48.085 align:middle line:84%
And you're not just that person
who wants that particular goal.

00:44:48.085 --> 00:44:50.121 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: So there's a lot
of different influences.

00:44:50.121 --> 00:44:51.756 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: There's a
lot of different yous

00:44:51.756 --> 00:44:52.690 align:middle line:90%
that are going on.

00:44:52.690 --> 00:44:55.793 align:middle line:84%
And so, if you identify
with the big dreamer,

00:44:55.793 --> 00:44:58.996 align:middle line:84%
then you have a feeling
of almost satisfaction

00:44:58.996 --> 00:45:00.331 align:middle line:90%
with whatever happens.

00:45:00.331 --> 00:45:03.568 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: There's a lot of
different observers, as well,

00:45:03.568 --> 00:45:05.036 align:middle line:90%
affecting and impacting it.

00:45:05.036 --> 00:45:07.138 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, there's
different illusions

00:45:07.138 --> 00:45:08.506 align:middle line:90%
of different observers.

00:45:08.506 --> 00:45:11.309 align:middle line:84%
Because one-- There's illusions
of-- there's only one observer

00:45:11.309 --> 00:45:12.410 align:middle line:90%
in all this stuff.

00:45:12.410 --> 00:45:13.077 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You.

00:45:13.077 --> 00:45:13.578 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: You.

00:45:13.578 --> 00:45:15.112 align:middle line:90%
And you are the big observer.

00:45:15.112 --> 00:45:16.914 align:middle line:90%
But you have to remember that.

00:45:16.914 --> 00:45:17.748 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fascinating.

00:45:17.748 --> 00:45:19.050 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely fascinating.

00:45:19.050 --> 00:45:22.086 align:middle line:84%
All right, so how--
I asked you about how

00:45:22.086 --> 00:45:23.921 align:middle line:84%
this could change
our past or present.

00:45:23.921 --> 00:45:26.257 align:middle line:84%
You've said many
times here that I

00:45:26.257 --> 00:45:28.459 align:middle line:90%
am the universe, that I am God.

00:45:28.459 --> 00:45:29.694 align:middle line:90%
You've said that many times.

00:45:29.694 --> 00:45:32.897 align:middle line:84%
I've heard this statement
before in different references

00:45:32.897 --> 00:45:34.198 align:middle line:90%
and texts and so forth.

00:45:34.198 --> 00:45:37.435 align:middle line:84%
How does quantum
physics explain that?

00:45:37.435 --> 00:45:39.036 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: It explains
it by bringing

00:45:39.036 --> 00:45:44.141 align:middle line:84%
into our way of understanding
how the universe gets created

00:45:44.141 --> 00:45:49.213 align:middle line:84%
that there must be a
field which allows matter

00:45:49.213 --> 00:45:51.349 align:middle line:90%
to come into existence.

00:45:51.349 --> 00:45:56.320 align:middle line:84%
And without this field,
and in the currents

00:45:56.320 --> 00:45:57.855 align:middle line:84%
searched there--
because they don't

00:45:57.855 --> 00:46:01.726 align:middle line:84%
get into mind of God type of
talk in physics laboratories.

00:46:01.726 --> 00:46:06.430 align:middle line:84%
They call it the Higgs
field, H-I-G-G-S field,

00:46:06.430 --> 00:46:11.235 align:middle line:84%
which they believe is necessary
for producing the interactions

00:46:11.235 --> 00:46:15.906 align:middle line:84%
for these spin one half light
particles to bounce back

00:46:15.906 --> 00:46:19.143 align:middle line:84%
and forth in a zig zag dance,
appearing to slow down,

00:46:19.143 --> 00:46:22.046 align:middle line:84%
and therefore appear
as material existence.

00:46:22.046 --> 00:46:29.754 align:middle line:84%
So this minefield is what is
the essence of quantum physics.

00:46:29.754 --> 00:46:32.390 align:middle line:84%
And therefore the
essence of reality.

00:46:32.390 --> 00:46:33.057 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Reality.

00:46:33.057 --> 00:46:33.824 align:middle line:90%
I was going to say.

00:46:33.824 --> 00:46:36.827 align:middle line:84%
I didn't want to say it
before you because I'm just

00:46:36.827 --> 00:46:38.029 align:middle line:90%
grasping this along with you.

00:46:38.029 --> 00:46:38.863 align:middle line:90%
But I did get it.

00:46:38.863 --> 00:46:40.798 align:middle line:90%
A reality, yeah, absolutely.

00:46:40.798 --> 00:46:43.367 align:middle line:90%
All right, so, I love this.

00:46:43.367 --> 00:46:44.635 align:middle line:90%
You guys are really engaging.

00:46:44.635 --> 00:46:47.304 align:middle line:84%
There's great questions coming
in on Facebook and Twitter.

00:46:47.304 --> 00:46:50.274 align:middle line:90%
So, is time really speeding up?

00:46:50.274 --> 00:46:51.942 align:middle line:84%
One of our Facebook
listeners is asking.

00:46:51.942 --> 00:46:52.610 align:middle line:90%
I love it.

00:46:52.610 --> 00:46:53.244 align:middle line:90%
I love it, yeah.

00:46:53.244 --> 00:46:56.914 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, you know, time
speeding up or slowing down

00:46:56.914 --> 00:47:02.586 align:middle line:84%
depends upon which way
you have of observing it.

00:47:02.586 --> 00:47:08.526 align:middle line:84%
So, yes you can experience time
speeding up or slowing down.

00:47:08.526 --> 00:47:11.762 align:middle line:84%
And we all know various
ways of talking about that.

00:47:11.762 --> 00:47:15.066 align:middle line:84%
Put your finger on a hot
stove and time goes very fast.

00:47:15.066 --> 00:47:16.200 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:47:16.200 --> 00:47:18.636 align:middle line:84%
Or if you have a busy
day, time goes very fast.

00:47:18.636 --> 00:47:19.136 align:middle line:90%
Yes

00:47:19.136 --> 00:47:20.805 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: Right.

00:47:20.805 --> 00:47:25.042 align:middle line:84%
If you're making love
with your favorite lover,

00:47:25.042 --> 00:47:27.545 align:middle line:84%
time can sometimes goes
just the other way around.

00:47:27.545 --> 00:47:30.181 align:middle line:84%
I mean, go too fast,
too slow, depending

00:47:30.181 --> 00:47:30.648 align:middle line:84%
on how well you like
the other person.

00:47:30.648 --> 00:47:31.115 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Your observer.

00:47:31.115 --> 00:47:32.116 align:middle line:90%
Being the observer, yes.

00:47:32.116 --> 00:47:34.685 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: So, there's
various ways that time

00:47:34.685 --> 00:47:36.754 align:middle line:84%
could go depending
upon the observer.

00:47:36.754 --> 00:47:38.856 align:middle line:84%
And what we're looking
at are relative events.

00:47:38.856 --> 00:47:40.691 align:middle line:84%
But in relativity
theory, we also

00:47:40.691 --> 00:47:43.728 align:middle line:84%
know that a moving
observer experiences

00:47:43.728 --> 00:47:49.500 align:middle line:84%
time running slow in comparison
with a rest observer.

00:47:49.500 --> 00:47:52.436 align:middle line:84%
But what that deals
with is really

00:47:52.436 --> 00:47:56.907 align:middle line:84%
two different ways of observing
and trying to compare them,

00:47:56.907 --> 00:48:02.980 align:middle line:84%
one to the other, based upon one
or the other's point of view.

00:48:02.980 --> 00:48:07.251 align:middle line:84%
Because from each point of
view, the other guy is moving.

00:48:07.251 --> 00:48:10.454 align:middle line:84%
And so, from my point of
view, if other guy's moving,

00:48:10.454 --> 00:48:13.190 align:middle line:84%
his time runs slow,
from his point of view,

00:48:13.190 --> 00:48:15.793 align:middle line:84%
since I'm the one moving, he
would say my time runs slow.

00:48:15.793 --> 00:48:17.394 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: You gave an
example of two cars

00:48:17.394 --> 00:48:19.964 align:middle line:84%
moving parallel to each other
but moving at the same time.

00:48:19.964 --> 00:48:22.199 align:middle line:84%
And it feels like you're
moving at the same time.

00:48:22.199 --> 00:48:26.070 align:middle line:84%
One could go faster or slower
as you move along, right?

00:48:26.070 --> 00:48:28.105 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, the
relative speed-- yes.

00:48:28.105 --> 00:48:30.241 align:middle line:84%
You would say
that-- exactly that,

00:48:30.241 --> 00:48:32.109 align:middle line:84%
that if you're going
along at the same speed,

00:48:32.109 --> 00:48:34.145 align:middle line:90%
it looks like nobody's moving.

00:48:34.145 --> 00:48:35.946 align:middle line:84%
But if one guy
starts to speed up,

00:48:35.946 --> 00:48:39.216 align:middle line:84%
it looks like you're going very
slow relative to the other guy.

00:48:39.216 --> 00:48:41.919 align:middle line:84%
And he's-- or you could
say you're standing still

00:48:41.919 --> 00:48:43.254 align:middle line:90%
and he's going backwards.

00:48:43.254 --> 00:48:44.088 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: OK.

00:48:44.088 --> 00:48:46.590 align:middle line:84%
All right, so, another question
coming in from Facebook.

00:48:46.590 --> 00:48:50.795 align:middle line:84%
Can we actually time travel
and transcend space and time?

00:48:50.795 --> 00:48:52.496 align:middle line:84%
I think you have a
slide about that.

00:48:52.496 --> 00:48:58.169 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, basically, we are
time traveling all of the time.

00:48:58.169 --> 00:49:04.108 align:middle line:84%
It's just that we've learned
to hold onto, or fixate, on who

00:49:04.108 --> 00:49:06.343 align:middle line:84%
and what we are at
the particular moment.

00:49:06.343 --> 00:49:08.479 align:middle line:84%
And that fixation
becomes so ingrained--

00:49:08.479 --> 00:49:09.547 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Boy, do we, yes.

00:49:09.547 --> 00:49:11.482 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: --that it becomes
like-- have you ever

00:49:11.482 --> 00:49:14.752 align:middle line:84%
seen people that are
always tight fisted?

00:49:14.752 --> 00:49:16.420 align:middle line:84%
And you say, well,
relax your hand.

00:49:16.420 --> 00:49:17.755 align:middle line:90%
Well, I can't.

00:49:17.755 --> 00:49:22.259 align:middle line:84%
That's how we are about our ego,
I. We just can't open it up.

00:49:22.259 --> 00:49:24.061 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: We get so
wrapped up in who we are.

00:49:24.061 --> 00:49:25.863 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: We're wrapped up
in who and what we are.

00:49:25.863 --> 00:49:27.298 align:middle line:84%
So we have the
illusion-- then it

00:49:27.298 --> 00:49:29.233 align:middle line:84%
seems like what I'm
talking about is nonsense.

00:49:29.233 --> 00:49:31.268 align:middle line:84%
What do you mean take
time-- I can't time travel.

00:49:31.268 --> 00:49:32.303 align:middle line:90%
I'm here now.

00:49:32.303 --> 00:49:33.737 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, let
me ask about you.

00:49:33.737 --> 00:49:38.776 align:middle line:84%
When someone asks you what
do you do, what do you say?

00:49:38.776 --> 00:49:40.711 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: It depends
on what they ask me.

00:49:40.711 --> 00:49:42.112 align:middle line:84%
I mean, if they
ask me about do I

00:49:42.112 --> 00:49:43.581 align:middle line:84%
time travel or
something like that.

00:49:43.581 --> 00:49:43.881 align:middle line:90%
You know what I mean?

00:49:43.881 --> 00:49:45.216 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, like
when they say hi, Fred.

00:49:45.216 --> 00:49:46.383 align:middle line:90%
What do you do for a living?

00:49:48.919 --> 00:49:50.454 align:middle line:90%
I love it.

00:49:50.454 --> 00:49:58.195 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: Well, my basic
thing that I do, I breathe.

00:49:58.195 --> 00:50:00.431 align:middle line:90%
I smell.

00:50:00.431 --> 00:50:02.666 align:middle line:90%
I hear.

00:50:02.666 --> 00:50:04.535 align:middle line:90%
I taste.

00:50:04.535 --> 00:50:06.570 align:middle line:90%
I touch.

00:50:06.570 --> 00:50:10.007 align:middle line:90%
I think, therefore I am.

00:50:10.007 --> 00:50:10.841 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good answer.

00:50:10.841 --> 00:50:14.445 align:middle line:84%
Very good answer, no, that's
perfect coming from you.

00:50:14.445 --> 00:50:18.616 align:middle line:84%
One of the listeners is asking--
Heather-- do you meditate?

00:50:18.616 --> 00:50:20.117 align:middle line:84%
Tell us a little
bit about your--

00:50:20.117 --> 00:50:21.619 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: I'd like
to talk about that.

00:50:21.619 --> 00:50:23.888 align:middle line:84%
Because meditation
is a word that

00:50:23.888 --> 00:50:26.390 align:middle line:90%
can be very easily confused.

00:50:26.390 --> 00:50:30.728 align:middle line:84%
And it may not mean
what you think it means.

00:50:30.728 --> 00:50:33.430 align:middle line:84%
Meditation, for most of us,
in our business lifetimes,

00:50:33.430 --> 00:50:37.201 align:middle line:84%
means stopping and
getting off the trolley,

00:50:37.201 --> 00:50:42.406 align:middle line:84%
and sitting still, and going om
mani padme hum, or oh, money,

00:50:42.406 --> 00:50:45.943 align:middle line:84%
pad my home, or whatever
you call meditation.

00:50:45.943 --> 00:50:48.445 align:middle line:84%
And it could mean any of
those kinds of things,

00:50:48.445 --> 00:50:49.747 align:middle line:90%
and that's a meditation.

00:50:49.747 --> 00:50:58.622 align:middle line:84%
But meditation can
also mean-- I smell.

00:50:58.622 --> 00:51:01.025 align:middle line:90%
I hear.

00:51:01.025 --> 00:51:02.726 align:middle line:90%
I listen.

00:51:02.726 --> 00:51:04.528 align:middle line:90%
I taste.

00:51:04.528 --> 00:51:06.764 align:middle line:90%
I touch.

00:51:06.764 --> 00:51:08.866 align:middle line:90%
I feel.

00:51:08.866 --> 00:51:13.837 align:middle line:84%
Meditation can be the
awareness of the wonders

00:51:13.837 --> 00:51:14.772 align:middle line:90%
of your own existence.

00:51:17.841 --> 00:51:21.245 align:middle line:84%
In Buddhist
meditation technique,

00:51:21.245 --> 00:51:23.280 align:middle line:84%
you think all they do
is sit and meditate.

00:51:23.280 --> 00:51:23.781 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No.

00:51:23.781 --> 00:51:24.548 align:middle line:90%
>>FRED: No.

00:51:24.548 --> 00:51:26.717 align:middle line:90%
They do walking meditation.

00:51:26.717 --> 00:51:28.953 align:middle line:90%
And what do they have you do?

00:51:28.953 --> 00:51:34.058 align:middle line:84%
Wake up and smell the
flowers, feel the wind,

00:51:34.058 --> 00:51:37.261 align:middle line:90%
listen to the air.

00:51:37.261 --> 00:51:40.631 align:middle line:84%
Meditation could
be a slowing down.

00:51:40.631 --> 00:51:42.566 align:middle line:90%
It could be a speeding up.

00:51:42.566 --> 00:51:44.468 align:middle line:84%
You're a runner,
and you're running.

00:51:44.468 --> 00:51:47.071 align:middle line:84%
You're a baseball player, and
you're about to hit a ball.

00:51:47.071 --> 00:51:49.940 align:middle line:84%
Meditation will allow you to
hit the ball even though it's

00:51:49.940 --> 00:51:53.043 align:middle line:84%
coming at you at nearly
100 miles per hour.

00:51:53.043 --> 00:51:58.015 align:middle line:84%
Meditation is the aware--
is putting your awareness

00:51:58.015 --> 00:52:01.685 align:middle line:84%
to work, so to speak,
without working

00:52:01.685 --> 00:52:03.654 align:middle line:84%
at putting your
awareness to work.

00:52:03.654 --> 00:52:05.456 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That's a
beautiful thing to say.

00:52:05.456 --> 00:52:08.792 align:middle line:84%
Especially now, at this hour
in the day, to have that moment

00:52:08.792 --> 00:52:09.727 align:middle line:90%
was really special.

00:52:09.727 --> 00:52:12.296 align:middle line:84%
Because we can tend to
get moving very, very

00:52:12.296 --> 00:52:13.697 align:middle line:90%
fast in this society.

00:52:13.697 --> 00:52:15.999 align:middle line:90%
So I appreciated that.

00:52:15.999 --> 00:52:17.601 align:middle line:84%
Fred Allan Wolfe
was in the movie

00:52:17.601 --> 00:52:18.836 align:middle line:90%
"What the Bleep do We Know?"

00:52:18.836 --> 00:52:24.308 align:middle line:84%
A great movie that we
have on Gaiam TV, as well.

00:52:24.308 --> 00:52:28.345 align:middle line:84%
And it's-- there's a piece
that we have from that movie.

00:52:28.345 --> 00:52:29.580 align:middle line:90%
And it's a great film.

00:52:29.580 --> 00:52:30.981 align:middle line:84%
I want you to take
a look at that.

00:52:30.981 --> 00:52:34.785 align:middle line:84%
It kind of encapsulates
what we have to say.

00:52:34.785 --> 00:52:37.788 align:middle line:84%
>>FRED: First of all, let's
talk about the subatomic world.

00:52:37.788 --> 00:52:40.324 align:middle line:84%
And then we'll talk about what
it's telling us about reality.

00:52:40.324 --> 00:52:42.826 align:middle line:84%
The first thing I want to tell
you about the subatomic world

00:52:42.826 --> 00:52:44.762 align:middle line:84%
is it's totally
a fantasy created

00:52:44.762 --> 00:52:48.632 align:middle line:84%
by mad physicists trying to
figure out what the heck is

00:52:48.632 --> 00:52:51.201 align:middle line:84%
going when they do these
little experiments.

00:52:51.201 --> 00:52:54.505 align:middle line:84%
By little experiments, I mean
big energy in little spaces

00:52:54.505 --> 00:52:56.273 align:middle line:90%
and little pieces of time.

00:52:56.273 --> 00:52:58.976 align:middle line:84%
It gets pretty nutty at
that realm of things.

00:52:58.976 --> 00:53:00.878 align:middle line:84%
And so, subatomic
physics was invented

00:53:00.878 --> 00:53:03.380 align:middle line:90%
to try to figure that all out.

00:53:03.380 --> 00:53:05.149 align:middle line:84%
We need a new
science down there.

00:53:05.149 --> 00:53:06.884 align:middle line:90%
It's called quantum physics.

00:53:06.884 --> 00:53:12.356 align:middle line:84%
And it is subject to a whole
range of debatable hypotheses,

00:53:12.356 --> 00:53:15.459 align:middle line:84%
thoughts, feelings,
intuitions as

00:53:15.459 --> 00:53:17.461 align:middle line:84%
to what the heck
is really going on.

00:53:17.461 --> 00:53:19.797 align:middle line:84%
This leads, naturally,
to wonder do

00:53:19.797 --> 00:53:22.733 align:middle line:84%
people-- are people affecting
the world of reality

00:53:22.733 --> 00:53:23.834 align:middle line:90%
that they see?

00:53:23.834 --> 00:53:25.769 align:middle line:90%
You betcha they are.

00:53:25.769 --> 00:53:29.406 align:middle line:84%
Every single one of us affects
the reality that we see,

00:53:29.406 --> 00:53:33.243 align:middle line:84%
even if we try to hide
from that and play victim.

00:53:33.243 --> 00:53:35.746 align:middle line:90%
We all are doing it.

00:53:35.746 --> 00:53:37.314 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: That is--
that was beautifully

00:53:37.314 --> 00:53:39.016 align:middle line:84%
done by Will Arntz
and Betsy Chasse.

00:53:39.016 --> 00:53:39.917 align:middle line:90%
